prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: continuum>0.67mJy sources
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Each SG contains sources in a narrrow range of expected continuum flux density, so that the optimal integration time is used for every source

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our correlator setup is chosen to maximise continuum signal to noise and thus achieve our primary object with maximal efficiency. As a secondary goal, the setup will allow us to measure CO(3-2) with ~40km/s resolution at z=0.3 (expected line widths are ~200km/s) but even for these we would require only a total line flux integrated across the line width and across the spatial extent of the source(s).

We request 1.0 arcsec resolution at 270 GHz for precise positions that will conclusively determine whether the sub-mm source is coincident with the optical. There are two scenarios to consider: the primary objective is to count the cases where the continuum source is resolved into a high-z point source spatially offset from the optical position, and such objects will be unresolved at 1 arcsec (>6kpc at z>0.5). The second scenario is that the source is at z=0.3 and is potentially resolved into multiple objects, in which case 1 arcsec resolution (=4.5kpc) would resolve multiple galaxies but would not significantly resolve emission within a single galaxy. The maximum recoverable scale in configurations C36-1/2 is 9 arcsec at 270 GHz (40 kpc at z=0.3), which is much larger than the expected extent of any source. The maximum angular scale of a galaxy is 2 arcsec = 9kpc.

Our RMS is based on continuum detection. We obtain the continuum RMS by estimating the total estimated flux density (obtained from a modified blackbody fit to Herschel/SPIRE photometry extrapolated to 270 GHz, see Science Case) and dividing this by 6. Assuming a single point source (appropriate in the case of a high-z lensed source, as required by our primary objective), this provides S/N=6. In the alternative scenario where the SPIRE source is resolved into one or more low-z galaxies, a single galaxy would only be marginally resolved and the peak S/N would be close to 6, and if the flux comes from 2 or 3 galaxies they would each have average S/N =3 or 2, although we would maximise this by smoothing the map to a lower resolution. In any case if no object is individually detected we can obtain the total flux in apertures over all the optical galaxies in the field of view and see if any flux is missing from the expectation. The line flux is calculated from a modified blackbody fit (beta=1.8) to the full Herschel 100-500mum photometry used to obtain total LIR, and assuming L_CO (Kkm/s pc^2)=LIR/60 (Lsun) (see Science Case)

We have selected a non-standard central frequency of 261 GHz (representative frequency 270 GHz) because this allows us to detect CO(3-2) at 0.273<z<0.292 or 0.353<z<0.375. Although our primary goal is to detect continuum, the detection of a line at the redshift of the optical candidates would falsify our hypothesis that the submm source is lensed, and adds considerable value for secondary science objectives without the need for additional integration time or retuning. In terms of atmospheric transmission, the chosen frequencies are little different to the standard continuum setup: the basebands will avoid atmospheric lines and the ratio of transmission at 270 GHz to that of the standard 242 GHz is 0.94 (PWV=5mm) or 0.99 (PWV=1mm). Hence the frequency setup chosen does not significantly affect sensitivity.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to use 3.6 hours in Band 6 to perform a simple yet influential test of the reliability of optical counterparts to sub-mm sources in the Herschel-ATLAS survey. Single-dish sub-mm surveys are one of the most efficient ways of sampling star formation across cosmic time. A key ingredient is unambiguous identification of multi-wavelength counterparts to sources in low-resolution images, which are needed to obtain redshift distributions, convert source counts into luminosity functions, and measure intrinsic physical properties. Bourne et al (2014) found compelling evidence that widespread weak lensing in the H-ATLAS source population could significantly contaminate the counterpart identifications, a problem which has received little attention in the past. The contribution of strong lensing to the sub-mm source population is a popular topic, but the more subtle effects of weak lensing remain poorly constrained by observations, despite being much more common and being an important ingredient in models. This proposal requires only a modest time to image a large and representative sample, and will achieve significant results which are applicable to the wider population.
